
<p>
  What links everything together? How does a mine in Nevada link to A Community In Oklahoma Banning data centers from being built on their land? Well, essentially we are in the same boat, wanting to prevent a corporate takeover of the land, which usually ends in a community economically ravenged, residents put out of their homes, and jobs that were supposed to help never coming into fruition. It shows a collective idea, that is pushed by Government, not only the Government Of the United States of America, but also world wide. From the extraction of raw metals from the ground, to the data that is received to your router, the cost of a data center is unimaginable. Not only by the measurable, today scale that we see, but for the future of man, where a future in which all land that can be taken advantage of is done so. Where data that flows through the data center worth more then those that maintain it. That is the dystopian future we head towards, with these canary's in the mine being the first to sing. The United States allowing these corporations to work behind closed doors, supporting them as well as essentially encouraging them, shows that there is no stopping data centers from growing with the courts. Only with the people. It is a high likely hood that the Thacker Pass lithium mine, has lithium that is circulating around each of our devices, meaning that we too, in one way are responsible, That links us to this atrocity that is being committed to land, that is for our nations future to prosper. We must protect the land, as the Indigenous have shown us for centuries, that if we take care of the land, it will take care of us back. From the Federal government stalking protesters that fight against the root of data centers, to tech companies strong manning smaller communities into signing unfair NDA's, the only way that has shown to stop it would be community intervention, such as The Great Seminole Nation of Oklahoma couragesly showed to the nation. With the only way of preventing this from happening being forced onto the people, it shows the ever looping as a author wrote, "Death cycle" of colonialism and Eurocentric ideals happen in real time. With this being simply another lesson that will be most likely reappearing again in the not so distant future sadly. The only way to prevent this, and truly prosper as a civilization is refer to our history, take knowledge from lots non-Eurocentric communities, and attempt to heal this once beautiful country. 
</p>
